Bunchy top virus - USA (Hawaii) 20000505.0688
[1
Date: 7 May 2001
From: ProMED-mail <promed@promedmail.org>
Source: PACNEWS Pacific Islands Broadcasting Association News Services, 1
May 2001 [edited

Virus threatens banana crop
-------------------------------
NOUMEA, 30 April 2001: Authorities in New Caledonia's Northern Province
have declared a bunchy top disease alert in the northern part of the main
island. The alert comes after the French territory's economic development
and environment services (DDEE) were informed by a local farmer that his
banana trees were "suspicious."
DDEE immediately requested a special intervention from New Caledonia's
plant protection services, which confirmed the disease was bunchy top. The
disease, [which is caused by banana bunchy top nanavirus, seriously
affects banana production, and is spread by the banana aphid ( _Pentalonia
nigronervosa_). [The disease was first spotted in New Caledonia nearly 2
years ago, near the capital Noumea.
Stringent steps were then taken by authorities, including roadblocks
mounted by police to check for any motorists transporting infected banana
plants further into the Territory. In recent months, an intensive awareness
campaign has been mounted, including the production and broadcasting of
television spots.
Offenders caught transporting banana plants, infected or not, or refusing
to let their plantations be destroyed to prevent the disease spreading,
have been severely penalized by the local judiciary.
DDEE and plant protection services have meanwhile briefed the Northern
Provincial council members, in order to prevent what is seen as a
potentially severe blow to local food crops.
--
