[2
Date: 7 May 2001
From: ProMED-mail <promed@promedmail.org>
Source: PACNEWS 3, Oceania Flash/SPC, 1 May 2001 [edited

Massive banana preventive destruction to start
-------------------------------------------------
NOUMEA, 7 May 2001: Authorities in New Caledonia are poised to destroy
banana plants in the North province of the French territory in a bid to
prevent spreading of bunchy top disease, Reseau France Outre-mer (RFO)
reported on [7 May. The campaign is to start on 8 May after Territorial
and Provincial authorities last week decided to strike hard and
systematically eliminate all suspicious banana plants. Since the disease
broke out in the [area last week, an estimated 7 banana plantations are
said to be infested.
Plant protection authorities plan to systematically kill any suspicious
tree by injection of glyphosphate and re-plant with substitution crops that
would help some 65 affected families to survive.
Province President Paul Neaoutyine has responded by initiating a set of
measures, asking for the co-operation of all concerned agencies and
individuals. This included, like in the South [province, a ban of
transportation of any banana plant in the infected area.
Bunchy Top derives its name from the bunch formed by the young leaves at
the top of the banana plant, an indication that the tree had already been
infected for months.
In June 1999, New Caledonia's government took the first disease-fighting
steps: it introduced a compulsory declaration of any sick banana plants and
banned transportation of any banana plant in the infected areas.
--
ProMED-mail
promed@promedmail.org
[Banana bunchy top nanavirus causes one of the most serious diseases of
banana. The disease was first reported in Fiji in 1889 and Taiwan in 1900.
It is widespread in Southeast Asia, the Philippines, Taiwan, most of the
South Pacific islands, and parts of India and Africa. It is not known to be
present in Central or South America.
Two useful references on the disease are the following:
<http://www.agnet.org/library/article/eb418.html>
<http://ss.jircas.affrc.go.jp/engpage/jarq/33-1/kiritani/kiritani3.html> -
